   <question id="q1">
         <body>
            <p>What is the mean (expected) annual gain for a policy of this type?  In other words, what is the mean of X?  
            </p>
         </body>
         <short_answer id="A"/>
         <part>
            <response input="A" match="*" score="1"/>
            <explanation>
               <p>Using the definition of the mean of a discrete random variable, we will average the possible values weighted by their corresponding probabilities.</p>
               <p>Mean of X =
                  (1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145334-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>350
                  -
                  100<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145336-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>000)(.002)
                  +
                  (1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145340-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>350
                  -
                  50<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145341-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>000)(.008)
                  +
                  1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145345-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>350(.99)
                  = 750.</p>
               <p>The expected gain of such a policy is $750. Since the insurance company probably
                  sells a lot of policies of this type, in the majority of them (99%) the company
                  will gain money
                  ($1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145359-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>350),
                  and in the remaining 1% of
                  the<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145433-0500"?>m<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145432-0500" content=" time"?>,
                  it will lose (either
                  1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145439-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>350
                  -
                  100<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145440-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>000
                  or
                  1<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145442-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>350
                  -
                  5<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101121T145443-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>0000).
                  Averaging over all such policies, the company is going to make about $750 from
                  each such fire insurance policy. </p>
            </explanation>
         </part>
